      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Property Management Fees in Brisbane: What Investors Need to Know Before Selling
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Management costs directly affect what your investment property is worth to a buyer. Here is how the fees work, how they affect net yield calculations, and what to prepare before you list.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When an investor buyer is assessing the price they are willing to pay for a Brisbane rental property, they are not just looking at the current rent. They are working through a calculation of net yield: what the property actually returns after all the costs of ownership are deducted. Property management fees are one of the most significant and often underestimated items in that calculation. As a seller, understanding how these fees work and how buyers assess them will help you present your property in the strongest possible light.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The management fee: what it covers and what it costs</h2>
      <p>The management fee is the ongoing weekly charge paid to the property manager for looking after the tenancy. It covers rent collection, attending to tenant enquiries, coordinating routine maintenance, conducting periodic inspections, managing lease renewals, and the day-to-day administration of the tenancy agreement.</p>

      <p>In Brisbane, management fees typically range from 7% to 10% of weekly rent plus GST. The specific rate depends on the agency, the property's location, and the type of property. Inner-city apartments and properties managed by premium agencies at the higher end of the market will often sit at the lower end of this range. More suburban or regional properties, or those managed by agencies that price more aggressively to win business, may sit higher.</p>

      <p>On a rental of $700 per week at an 8.5% management fee, the weekly management cost is $59.50, or approximately $3,094 per year before GST. This is a material annual cost that a buyer will factor into their yield calculation. A property with a management fee of 7.5% compared to one managed at 10% at the same rent level will show a meaningfully different net yield, which in turn affects what a yield-focused buyer will pay.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The letting fee and other charges</h2>
      <p>Beyond the management fee, property managers in Queensland typically charge a letting fee each time they find and place a new tenant. The letting fee covers advertising the property, conducting viewings, processing applications, completing reference checks, and preparing the tenancy agreement. In Queensland, letting fees are typically 1 to 2 weeks rent plus GST.</p>

      <p>On a $700 per week rental at 1.5 weeks letting fee, this is $1,050 plus GST each time a new tenant is placed. The frequency with which you turn over tenants is therefore a meaningful variable in the total annual cost of management. A property with a stable long-term tenant has incurred one letting fee over several years. A property with annual tenant turnover is paying the letting fee every year.</p>

      <p>Other fees that some property managers charge include a routine inspection fee (charged per inspection visit, often two to four times per year), a lease renewal fee when an existing tenancy is extended rather than re-let, a maintenance coordination fee calculated as a percentage of repair and maintenance costs, and an end-of-financial-year statement fee. These are smaller charges but they add up over a full year of management.</p>

      <p>When you review your property management agreement before selling, look at all of the fees listed, not just the headline management rate. Buyers who ask for a copy of the management agreement will do exactly this, and they will use the full fee schedule to build their cost model.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How buyers calculate net yield</h2>
      <p>A buyer focused on investment return will work through a net yield calculation before making an offer. The starting point is gross rental income: the current weekly rent multiplied by 52. From this, they will deduct the annualised cost of every foreseeable expense: property management fees (management rate plus letting fee allowance), council rates, water rates, landlord insurance, body corporate levies (if applicable), allowance for routine repairs and maintenance, and any vacancy allowance.</p>

      <p>To illustrate with approximate figures: a property renting at $600 per week generates $31,200 in gross annual rent. Deducting management fees at 8.5% ($2,652), a letting fee allowance at 1.5 weeks per year ($900), insurance ($1,500), council rates ($1,800), water rates ($900), body corporate levies (nil, freehold house), and a modest maintenance allowance ($1,500), the total deductions are approximately $9,252, leaving a net rental income of roughly $21,948. At a purchase price of $700,000, this is a net yield of approximately 3.1%.</p>

      <p>That net yield figure is what determines the investor's maximum offer price at any target return they require. A change in management costs of $1,000 per year at a 4% yield target implies a $25,000 change in what a buyer is willing to pay for the property. This is why management fees are not just an administrative detail; they are a direct input to pricing for investor buyers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The role of a rental appraisal when selling</h2>
      <p>If the current rent on your property has not been reviewed for 12 months or more, there is a reasonable chance it is sitting below market rate. This matters when you are selling because the asking rent is a key input to a buyer's yield calculation. A below-market rent produces a lower apparent yield at any given asking price, making the property look less attractive to investors than it actually is.</p>

      <p>A current rental appraisal from the property manager, or from a prospective property manager, establishes the market rent and demonstrates what an investor buyer can achieve once the current tenancy transitions. For some sellers, this is a meaningful tool for justifying a higher asking price when the current rent lags the market. Ask your property manager for a written rental appraisal in the same period you are getting your sales appraisal.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to prepare before listing your investment property</h2>
      <p>Investor buyers are more information-intensive than owner-occupier buyers. They want documentation that allows them to verify the income, assess the management costs, and model the return. Preparing the following before you list will make your property easier to sell and reduce the number of information requests that slow down a campaign.</p>

      <p>The current lease agreement shows the tenant's name, the weekly rent, the lease commencement date, the lease expiry date, and any special conditions. Buyers want to know whether there is a fixed term in place, when it expires, and at what rent. A lease with 12 months remaining at a well-reviewed market rent is attractive; a lease expiring in 6 weeks at a rate that has not been reviewed in 3 years is less so.</p>

      <p>A 12-month rental history confirms that the tenant has been paying rent consistently and on time. Consistent payment history is a genuine selling point that reduces a buyer's risk perception. If there have been rent arrears or disputes during the tenancy, your agent needs to know about these before the property is listed.</p>

      <p>The current property management agreement sets out the fees the property manager charges and the terms under which the management can be transferred to a new owner or a new manager. Buyers will want to review this before proceeding, so have a clean copy available early in the process.</p>

      <p>A 12-month income and expense statement from the property manager shows the actual costs over the past year and allows buyers to cross-check their projections against real figures. This is the most credible document you can provide for a buyer's due diligence process.</p>

